,Recommended,330100,20836732,"Posted: 29 January, 2016",all,Bushi,"Out of all the games I've gotten on Steam so far, this is the first one I've felt like writing a review for, mainly because I see a lot of potential in this one and hope for it to succeed. So keep in mind this is my first review and itisfor an Early Access game.Starting OffThis game is a sandbox through and through, focusing obviously on the construction of a customized ship and then allowing you to test it out within various game modes from a full campaign of sorts where you establish yourself with different factions that each have their focus on research types, a survival mode, random missions and more to come I am sure. Sure, there is no story, save a generic themed enemy that apparently is a threat for some reason, but let's admit that isn't what people play sandbox games for.There is already plenty of modules for making the ship function the way you like to play. Want a gunship? Make it happen. Want a ship that has more versatility in tools and tech? Do it. However, at the current point in the game, it feels like there is very limited uses for many of the different techs already available, and in time I hope to see more reasons and uses for it all.Graphically speaking, it's nothing impressive, but there's plenty of particle effects to keep things flashy enough to keep my attention. I still get the inner satisfaction when I destroy enemy ships to say the least, and the effects of the weapons and other modules feels appropriate for what they are/do. The music does its job at setting the feel for the missions and stuff, but tends to get a little repetitive after awhile and I have begun muting the music to play my own during my long sit down sessions with this game (three in total so far).PositivesExceptional Ship CustomizationBasic, But Helpful Tutorial (With exception of the negative below)Fully Rebindable Controls & Controller SupportA Developer Who Appears Interested In FeedbackNumerous Modes of Play With Challenge For AllNegativesRebindable Controls Do Not Fix Difficult ManeuveringModerate Learning Curve (Knowing which faction to help in the procedurally generated galaxy, and how it applies to your research is something I am still figuring out... could be helpful to explain that in the tutorial.)Neutral Factors(Things I believe will probably get better as development continues)Limited Mission Variety (Currently they could get repetitive for those who prefer variations)Few Reasons to Use Specific Module Types (This might be a personal preference thing)Occasional Bugs (To be expected with Early Access)More Control Options than Buttons on Controllers (I am sure the expected interface with the game is via keyboard and mouse, but the use of a controller is a very nice option when wanting to play casually, and it feels limited when you have to choose what abilities you want to have access to if using the controller.)AssessmentOverall this is a very entertaining experience for me, as I keep spending time trying to tweak my ships to be more streamlined, or trying to upgrade my modules. For an Early Access title, this one is one of few I have felt is worth the asking price, though I happened to find it on sale and became my replacement for another game since I can't play (and have chosen not to) Galactic Civilizations 3. With the level of customization, replayability due to a variety of game types, and the fact that the developer seems to be actively engaged with the playing community and offering frequent updates, I suggest you take a look at this game if it happens to be your cup of tea. Being still in development, it has plenty of potential to become a gem in my library.Personal Verdict8.5 / 10"
,Recommended,330100,29638135,Posted: 1 February,all,Fox,"This game is a fun top down space ship shooter. You can build your vessel from the ground up with modules you collect from winning battles. There are a wide range of modules that suit all play styles. You can design fast, slow, ranged, close-quarters, shielded, stealth, mine-layer, carriers, drones etc.There is a campaign which I guess is what most people play and it it challenging at the start but less so towards the end. Like most games, once you beat the technology curve the missions are still fun, but the outcome is pretty much predictable.This is a single player game so the AI needs to be smart - and it is. It's not perfect but it's effective, considering the AI needs to control any ship of any design so none of it can be scripted.There is an evolution mode where you don't play but watch AI ships fight each other. Winners will evolve into a new ship. You can watch generaton after generation evolve. Strictly for fun, science and interests sake but you can get some very interesting designs if you leave this sim running for a while. Also makes a great display/screen saver.  :)The developer is active and responsive to bugs. New content is being added post-release so the dev is supporting the customer base.There are one or two minor useability issues that I think have been outstanding for a long time that are yet to be addressed but that's not enough reason to avoid this game.I was reluctant to by a single-player top-down shooter but the way you can design a ship from the ground up and blast away at the AI is simply rewarding.  :)"
76561197993462247,Recommended,330100,17101733,"Posted: 17 July, 2015",all,Knockin' Boots,"If you're on the fence trying to decide whether or not to buy this game, I say go for it!When I came across this game, and I watched the video and looked at the screenshots and I thought ""MEH"".I would have passed it over, but at the time the game had a 100% rating on Steam. I figured OK, statistically speaking the reviews can't all be from friends and family. The game was on sale at the time so I took a chance. Am I ever glad I did! I've been playing the game for over a week. Steam says I've logged almost 30 hours in that time... how is that possible?! I work 2 jobs! But then I do the math and yeah... I think I've been playing the game too much.So why is the game so much fun?Weapons feel great!They have weight. I love the way my lasers rip into the hulls of enemy vessels. Missiles, torpedoes, they all FEEL good.Customizability.My battleship has like, 10 different action keys. One to fire lasers, one to fire long range weapons, one to launch my interceptors, one to open/close the main torpedo ports, one to fire the torpedoes, one for emergency hyperspace, etc etc. I sometimes get the keys mixed up and I accidentally hyperspace into an enemy ship when I was trying to turn on the emergency generator. I should really move that keybind to somewhere else.Battles are intense.No matter how awesome your ship gets, you still need to keep your eyes on the smaller enemy ships because they can still hurt you.Constant updates!The developer updated the game at least twice in the week I've had the game.Still, the game isn't perfect:It's Early Access.The game is a work-in-progress, but I've had no crashes except on the first day (but that was because the dev was working on the game). But there is a TON of content.Ships look... not quite like starships.Because it's kinda like lego. If you stick weapon modules onto a drive module and add some ore container boxes... well it's not gonna look pretty. Still, you can build some pretty respectable looking starships. But alot of times your ship is going to look like you just crazy-glued a bunch of ship parts together. Beware my garbage scow!AI isn't perfect.The AI is good enough to put up a decent fight most of the time. But then for no reason it'll hyperspace into an asteroid.So the game is definitely worth the price, full or on sale."
